"'''Lola'''" is a song written by [[Ray Davies]] and performed by English [[Rock music|rock]] band [[the Kinks]] on their album ''[[Lola Versus Powerman and the Moneygoround, Part One]]''. The song details a romantic encounter between a young man and a <!-- PLEASE read the section titled "Playful ambiguity" on this article's talk page before deleting the word "possible" that follows. Thanks. --> possible <!-- see preceding comment --> [[transvestite]], whom he meets in a club in [[Soho]], London. In the song, the narrator describes his confusion towards Lola, who "walked like a woman but talked like a man". Although Ray Davies claims that the incident was inspired by a true encounter experienced by the band's manager, alternative explanations for the song have been given by drummer [[Mick Avory]].

The song was released in the United Kingdom on 12 June 1970, while in the United States it was released on 28 June 1970. Commercially, the single reached number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]]<ref name="UK charts">{{cite web|title=KINKS|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/11246/KINKS/|website=Official Charts|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> and number nine on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=chartsUS>{{cite web|title=The Kinks – Awards|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-kinks-mn0000100160/awards|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref> Due to its controversial subject matter and use of the brand name [[Coca-Cola]], the single received backlash and even bans in Britain and Australia. The single version (mono) used the words "cherry cola" while the album version (stereo) uses the name "Coca-Cola". The track has since become one of The Kinks' most iconic and popular songs, later being ranked number 422 on "[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]" as well as number 473 on the "[[NME]]'s 500 Greatest Songs Of All Time" list.<ref name="nme 500">{{cite web|title=The 500 Greatest Songs Of All Time – 473. The Kinks – 'Lola'|url=http://www.nme.com/photos/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-500-401/330541#/photo/39|publisher=''[[New Musical Express]]''|accessdate=2 June 2015}}</ref>

Since its release, "Lola" has appeared on multiple compilation and live albums. In 1980, a live version of the song from the album ''[[One for the Road (The Kinks album)|One for the Road]]'' was released as a single in the US and some European countries, becoming a minor hit. In the Netherlands it became #1, just as in 1970 with the studio version. Other versions include live renditions from 1972's ''[[Everybody's in Show-Biz]]'' and 1996's ''[[To the Bone (The Kinks album)|To the Bone]]''. The "Lola" character also made an appearance in the lyrics of the band's 1981 song, "[[Destroyer (The Kinks song)|Destroyer]]".

==Background==
{{quote box|quote=It was a real experience in a club. I was asked to dance by somebody who was a fabulous looking woman. I said "no thank you". And she went in a cab with my manager straight afterwards. It's based on a personal experience. But not every word.|source= – Ray Davies{{sfn|Hasted|2011}}|width=25%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}

Ray Davies has claimed that he was inspired to write "Lola" after Kinks manager Robert Wace spent a night in Paris dancing with a [[transvestite]].{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|p=171}} Davies said of the incident, "In his apartment, Robert had been dancing with this black woman, and he said, 'I'm really onto a thing here.' And it was okay until we left at six in the morning and then I said, 'Have you seen the stubble?' He said 'Yeah', but he was too pissed [intoxicated] to care, I think".{{sfn|Savage|1984}}

Drummer [[Mick Avory]] has offered an alternative explanation for the song's lyrics, claiming that "Lola" was partially inspired by Avory's frequenting of transvestite bars in west London.{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|pp=171–172}} Avory said, "We used to know this character called Michael McGrath. He used to hound the group a bit, because being called The Kinks did attract these sorts of people. He used to come down to ''[[Top of the Pops]]'', and he was publicist for John Stephen's shop in Carnaby Street. He used to have this place in Earl's Court, and he used to invite me to all these drag queen acts and transsexual pubs. They were like secret clubs. And that's where Ray [Davies] got the idea for 'Lola'. When he was invited too, he wrote it while I was getting drunk".{{sfn|Hasted|2011}}

Despite claims that the song was written about a supposed date between Ray Davies and [[Candy Darling]], Davies has since claimed this rumour to be false, saying that the two only went out to dinner together and that he had known the whole time that Darling was trans.{{sfn|Hasted|2011}}

In his autobiography, [[Dave Davies]] said that he came up with the music for what would become "Lola", noting that brother Ray added the lyrics after hearing it.{{sfn|Hickey|2012|p=138}} In a 1990 interview, Dave Davies stated that "Lola" was written in a similar fashion to "[[You Really Got Me]]" in that the two worked on Ray's basic skeleton of the song, saying that the song was more of a collaborative effort than many believed.<ref name=davedavies>{{cite web|last1=McCue|first1=Danny|title=Dave Davies – Out Of the Ordinary|url=http://www.davedavies.com/articles/gm_0290.htm|website=Davedavies.com|publisher=Guitar Magazine|accessdate=11 April 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6XfDYXak2?url=http://www.davedavies.com/articles/gm_0290.htm|archivedate=9 April 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

==Writing and recording==
{{quote box|quote=I remember going into a music store on Shaftesbury Avenue when we were about to make "Lola". I said, "I want to get a really good guitar sound on this record, I want a Martin". And in the corner they had this old 1938 Dobro [resonating guitar] that I bought for $150. I put them together on "Lola" which is what makes that clangy sound: the combination of the Martin and the Dobro with heavy compression.|source= – Ray Davies{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}}|width=30%|align=left|style=padding:8px;}}

Written in April 1970, "Lola" was cited by Ray Davies as the first song he wrote following a break he took to act in the 1970 [[Play for Today]] film ''The Long Distance Piano Player''.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=139}} Davies said that he had initially struggled with writing an opening that would sell the song, but the rest of the song "came naturally".{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=139}}

Initial recordings of the song began in April 1970, but, as the band's bassist [[John Dalton (musician)|John Dalton]] remembered, recording for "Lola" took particularly long, stretching into the next month.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}} During April, four to five versions were attempted, utilizing different keys as well as varying beginnings and styles.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}} In May, new piano parts were added to the backing track by John Gosling, the band's new piano player that had just been auditioned.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}} Vocals were also added at this time. The song was then mixed during that month. Mick Avory remembered the recording sessions for the song positively, saying that it "was fun, as it was the Baptist's [John Gosling's] first recording with us".<ref name="kok mick interview">{{cite web|title="Not Many Drummers from West Molesey Have Done That!" – The Mick Avory Interview: Part 2|url=http://kastoffkinks.co.uk/Mick%20Avory%20interview%20part%202.htm|website=Kastoffkinks.uk|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>

The guitar opening on the song was produced as a result of combining the sound of a [[C. F. Martin & Company|Martin guitar]] and a vintage [[Dobro|Dobro resonating guitar]].{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|p=171}}{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}} Ray Davies cited this blend of guitar sounds for the song's unique guitar sound.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}}

==Release==
{{quote box|quote= I wanted to write a hit [with "Lola".] It wasn't just the song. it was the musical design. It wasn't a power chord song like "[[You Really Got Me]]". It was a power chord beginning. It needed a special acoustic guitar sound ... sonorous, growling, with an attack to it.|source= – Ray Davies, Radio 4's ''Master Tapes''{{sfn|Hasted|2011}}|width=20%|align=right|style=padding:8px;}}

Despite the chart success "Lola" would achieve, its fellow ''Lola vs. Powerman'' track "Powerman" was initially considered to be the first single from the album.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=140}} However, "Lola", which Ray Davies later claimed was an attempt to write a hit, was eventually decided on as the debut single release.{{sfn|Hasted|2011}}

"Lola" was released as a single in 1970.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=142}} In the UK, the [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] to the single was ''[[the Kinks Are the Village Green Preservation Society]]'' outtake "[[Berkeley Mews]]"{{sfn|Miller|2003|p=110–111}} while the Dave Davies-penned "Mindless Child of Motherhood" was used in the US.{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=142}} It became an unexpected chart smash for the Kinks, reaching number two in Britain<ref name="UK charts" /> and number nine in the United States.<ref name=chartsUS /> The single also saw success worldwide, reaching the top of the charts in Ireland, New Zealand, and South Africa, as well as the top 5 in Germany, Austria, Belgium, and Switzerland. The success of the single had important ramifications for the band's career at a critical time, allowing them to negotiate a new contract with [[RCA Records]], construct their own London Studio, and assume more creative and managerial control. In a 1970 interview, Dave Davies stated that, if "Lola" had been a failure, the band would have "gone on making records for another year or so and then drifted apart".{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=145}}

Although the track was a major hit for the band, Dave Davies did not enjoy the success of "Lola", saying, "In fact, when 'Lola' was a hit, it made me feel a bit uncomfortable. Because it was taking us out of a different sort of comfort zone, where we'd been getting into the work, and the writing and the musicality was more thought about. It did have that smell of: 'Oh blimey, not that again.' I found it a bit odd, that period. And then it got odder and weirder".{{sfn|Hasted|2011}} Mick Avory said that he "enjoyed the success" the band had with "Lola" and its follow-up, "[[Apeman (song)|Apeman]]".{{sfn|Hasted|2011}}

== Controversy ==
Originally, "Lola" saw controversy for its lyrics. In a ''[[Record Mirror]]'' article entitled "Sex Change Record: Kink Speaks", Ray Davies addressed the matter, saying, "It really doesn't matter what sex Lola is, I think she's alright".{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|p=172}} Some radio stations would fade the track out before implications of Lola's biological sex were revealed.{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|p=171}} On 18 November 1970, the song was banned in Australia because of its "controversial subject matter".{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=146}}

The BBC banned the track for a different reason. The original song recorded in [[Stereophonic sound|stereo]] had the word "[[Coca-Cola]]" in the lyrics, but because of BBC Radio's policy against [[product placement]], Ray Davies was forced to make a 6000-mile round-trip flight from New York to London and back on June 3, 1970, interrupting the band's American tour, to change those words to the generic "cherry cola" for the single release, which is included on various compilation albums as well.<ref name="NZ_Herald_10483279">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/radio-industry/news/article.cfm?c_id=295&objectid=10483279&ref=rss |title=Banning songs not a rare occurrence for the BBC |date=19 December 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=15 October 2011}}</ref><ref name="ucr rerecord">{{cite web|last1=Giles|first1=Jeff|title=45 Years Ago: Ray Davies Flies Across the Atlantic&nbsp;– Twice!&nbsp;– to Re-Record Two Words in ‘Lola’|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/kinks-lola-lyric-changes/|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref>{{refn|group=nb|Ray Davies later stated that, like in the lyrics of "Lola", he had actually drunk champagne that tastes like cola, saying, "I had a Californian champagne that tasted like it, in some kind of L.A. bordello tourist trap".<ref name="ucr rerecord" />}}

==Reception and legacy==
"Lola" received positive reviews from critics. Upon the single's release, the ''[[NME]]'' praised the song as "an engaging and sparkling piece with a gay Latin flavour and a catchy hook chorus".{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|p=172}}{{refn|group=nb|The ''NME'' later ranked the song number 473 on their "500 Greatest Songs Of All Time" list, calling it "the sweetest" account of "accidentally sleeping with a ladyboy".<ref name="nme 500" />}} ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said of the song at the time of its US release, "Currently a top ten British chart winner, this infectious rhythm item has all the ingredients to put the Kinks right back up the Hot 100 here with solid impact".{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=144}} ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' critic [[Paul Gambaccini]] called the song as "brilliant and a smash".{{sfn|Hinman|2004|p=148}}{{refn|group=nb|''Rolling Stone'' later ranked "Lola" at 422 on their 2004 list of the "[[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6596267/lola |title=The RS 500 Greatest Songs of All Time – 422: Lola – The Kinks |accessdate=2009-12-01 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917184302/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6596267/lola |archivedate=17 September 2008 |df= }}</ref> It was removed from the list on their 2011 revision of the ranking.}} Music critic [[Robert Christgau]], despite his mixed opinion on the ''Lola vs. Powerman'' album, praised the single as "astounding".<ref name=christgau>{{cite web|last1=Christgau|first1=Robert|title=The Kinks|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_artist.php?id=1464&name=The+Kinks|website=Robertchristgau.com}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] lauded the song for "its crisp, muscular sound, pitched halfway between acoustic folk and hard rock".<ref name=allmusic /> ''[[Ultimate Classic Rock]]'' ranked "Lola" as The Kinks' third best song, saying "the great guitar riff that feeds the song is one of Dave's all-time greatest".<ref name=UCR>{{cite web|last1=Gallucci|first1=Michael|title=Top 10 Kinks Songs|url=http://ultimateclassicrock.com/kinks-songs/|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref> ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' listed the track as the band's fourth best song.<ref name=paste>{{cite web|last1=Stiernberg|first1=Bonnie|title=The 15 Best Kinks Songs|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/04/the-15-best-kinks-songs-1.html|website=Pastemagazine.com|accessdate=4 April 2015}}</ref>

The song was also well-liked by the band. Mick Avory, who noted the song as one of the songs he was most proud to be associated with,<ref name="kok mick interview" /> said "I always liked 'Lola', I liked the subject. It's not like anything else. I liked it for that. We'd always take a different path".{{sfn|Hasted|2011}} In a 1983 interview, Ray Davies said, "I'm just very pleased I recorded it and more pleased I wrote it".<ref name=mtv>{{cite AV media |people=[[Mark Goodman|Goodman, Mark]] (interviewer)|date= |year=1983 |title=Groovy Movies |medium=Television production |publisher=MTV |ref= }}</ref> The band revisited the "Lola" character in the lyrics of their 1981 song, "[[Destroyer (The Kinks song)|Destroyer]]", a minor chart hit in America.{{sfn|Jovanovic|2014|p=245}}

Satirical artist [["Weird Al" Yankovic]] created a parody of the song called "[[Yoda (song)|Yoda]]", featuring lyrics about the ''[[Star Wars]]'' [[Yoda|character of the same name]], on his 1985 album ''[[Dare to Be Stupid]]''.<ref name="weird al parody">{{cite news|last1=Caulfield|first1=Philip|title=Weird Al Yankovic sings parody hit ‘Yoda’ with 13-year-old autistic girl|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/weird-al-sings-yoda-13-year-old-autistic-girl-article-1.2142749|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=6 June 2015}}</ref>

